===Legalization===

In some countries, prostitution is legal and regulated; although activities like pimping and street-walking are generally illegal. The degree of regulation varies by country; for example, not all countries require mandatory health checks because such checks are seen{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} as intrusive, a violation of human rights and discriminatory.

* Africa: [[Eritrea]];<ref name="arshad">{{cite web|last1=Arshad|first1=Dr. Md.|title=Prostitution in Africa: A sociological Study of Eritrea (North East Africa)|url=http://oldisrj.lbp.world/UploadedData/814.pdf|website=Indian Streams Research Journal;|accessdate=7 January 2018|date=March 2012}}</ref> [[Senegal]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Tunisia]]<ref name="spl" /> 
* Americas: [[Aruba]];<ref name="kempadoo">{{cite book|editor1-last=Kempadoo|editor1-first=Kamala |title=Sun, sex, and gold : tourism and sex work in the Caribbean|date=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham [u.a.]|isbn=978-0847695164}}</ref> [[Bolivia]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Bonaire]];<ref name="kempadoo"/> [[Chile]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Colombia]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Curaçao]];<ref name="kempadoo"/> [[Ecuador]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Nevada]] (except [[Carson City]] and [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark]], [[Douglas County, Nevada|Douglas]], [[Lincoln County, Nevada|Lincoln]], and [[Washoe County, Nevada|Washoe]] counties);<ref name="spl" /> [[Panama]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Peru]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Saba]];<ref name="kempadoo"/> [[Sint Eustatius]];<ref name="kempadoo"/> [[Sint Maarten]];<ref name="kempadoo"/> [[Uruguay]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Venezuela]];<ref name="spl" />
* Asia: [[Bangladesh]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Lebanon]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Taiwan]];<ref>{{cite web |url= https://redbrickdaily.com/legal-prostitution-coming-back-to-taipei/ |title= Legal Prostitution Coming Back To Taipei? |last= |first= |date= 15 August 2017 |website= Red Brick Daily |publisher= |access-date= 25 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref> [[Turkey]];<ref name="spl" />
* Europe: [[Austria]];<ref name="procon" /> [[Germany]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Greece]];<ref name="procon" /> [[Hungary]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Latvia]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Netherlands]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Switzerland]]<ref name="spl" />
* Oceania: Australia<ref name="spl" /> ([[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]], [[Northern Territory]], [[Queensland]], [[Tasmania]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]); [[Easter Island]]<ref>{{cite web|last1= PereyraUhrle|first1=Maria|title=Easter island Law|url=https://www.victoria.ac.nz/law/research/publications/about-nzacl/publications/cljpjdcp-journals/volume-12,-2006/pereyra.pdf|website=Victoria University|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref><ref name="spl" />

===Decriminalization===
The decriminalization of sex work is the removal of criminal penalties for sex work. Removing criminal prosecution for sex workers creates a safer and healthier environment<ref name="Aziza" /> and allows them to live with less social exclusion and stigma.<ref name="canada" />

* Africa: [[Cape Verde]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Cabo Verde: Código Penal (aprovado pelo Decreto Legislativo N° 4/2003 de 18 de Novembro de 2003)|url=http://www.wipo.int/wipolex/en/text.jsp?file_id=206287|website=[[World Intellectual Property Organization]]|accessdate=5 March 2018|language=pt|date=18 November 2003}}</ref> [[Guinea-Bissau]]<ref name="charts" /> 
* Oceania: [[Australia]]<ref name="spl">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=20 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> ([[New South Wales]]); [[New Zealand]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Niue]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Niue Act 1966 as at 20 September 2007|url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/lexdocs/laws/en/nu/nu001en.pdf|website=[[World Intellectual Property Organization]]|accessdate=6 February 2018|date=20 September 2007}}</ref> [[Pitcairn Islands]];<ref>{{cite web|title=The Laws of Pitcairn, Henderson, Ducie and Oeno Islands Volume 2|url=http://www.government.pn/Laws/Revised%20Laws%20of%20Pitcairn,%20Henderson,%20Ducie%20and%20Oeno%20Islands,%202017%20Rev.%20Ed.%20-%20Volume%202.pdf|website=Pitcairn Government|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> [[Tokelau]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of legislation of Tokelau|url=http://www.asia-pacific.undp.org/content/dam/rbap/docs/Research%20&%20Publications/hiv_aids/Pacific_HIV_Review/Tokelau_HIV_Ethics_and_HR_review_of_legislation.pdf |website=UNDP|accessdate=9 February 2018|language=en|date=March 2009}}</ref>

===Legality varies with local laws===

In these countries prostitution is permitted, prohibited or regulated by local laws rather than national laws. For example, in Mexico, prostitution is prohibited in some states but regulated in others.<ref name="spl" />

* Africa: [[Kenya]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Nigeria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigeria-law.org/Criminal%20Code%20Act-Tables.htm|title=Criminal Code Act-Tables|publisher=|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref><ref name="Ebun">{{cite news |last=Sessou |first=Ebun|date=October 15, 2011|title=Legalising Prostitution: Women give Ekweremadu hard knocks|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2011/10/legalising-prostitution-women-give-ekweremadu-hard-knocks/ |newspaper=Vanguard |location=Lagos |access-date= }}</ref>
* Americas: [[Argentina]];<ref name="panam">{{cite web|last1=Dubove|first1=Adam|title=Argentinean Sex Workers Demand the Right to Sell Their Own Bodies|url=https://panampost.com/adam-dubove/2015/12/04/argentinean-sex-workers-demand-the-right-to-exploit-their-own-bodies/|website=PanAm Post|accessdate=15 December 2017|date=4 December 2015}}</ref> [[El Salvador]];<ref name="procon" /> [[Mexico]];<ref name="spl" /> [[Nevada]] (USA);<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JLBDXNGLi88C&pg=PA9 |page=9 |title=Nevada Politics & Government: Conservatism in an Open Society |last=Driggs |first=Don W. |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |year=1996 |isbn=9780803217034}}</ref> 
